The Oathbroken Cohorts are former sworn bodies in Khardaan memory who violated custody obligations during crisis periods.
They are not a single organization but a historical category: military and administrative units in Khardaan that were formally sworn to custody duties and abandoned those duties under pressure.
Custody duties in Khardaan included protection of civilian populations during conflict, maintenance of prisoner treatment standards, and preservation of institutional records during evacuation.
The cohorts named in Khardaan's memory broke one or more of these obligations: abandoning civilians to advance unimpeded, executing prisoners outside sanctioned procedures, or destroying records rather than preserving them.
The designation oathbroken was formal, not colloquial: it appears in surviving Khardaan administrative records as a legal classification with specific consequences.
An oathbroken cohort lost its collective charter, its officers lost personal legal standing in Khardaan courts, and the unit's members could not individually swear new institutional oaths for a defined period.
The designation was intended as recoverable: after the defined period, members who had personally fulfilled remediation requirements could regain oath-standing.
Most of the named cohorts did not survive long enough to complete remediation: the crisis periods that produced the oath-breaking also produced the institutional collapse that made remediation impossible to pursue.
Khardaan's memory of the Oathbroken Cohorts therefore serves two functions: a historical record of specific violations and a standing legal classification with no surviving institution to close the cases.
The designation persists in Khardaan oral and documentary tradition as a warning category: these are the ways sworn bodies fail when crisis pressure overrides commitment.
Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw maintains cross-references to the Khardaan oathbroken classification as historical precedent for oath-violation adjudication.

