Midgaard's registry has limited direct documentation of the Khardaan Oathbroken Cohorts: Khardaan's administrative records do not map cleanly onto Midgaard's charter framework.
The Violet Compact's historical division has reviewed available Khardaan materials and classified the oathbroken designation as a functionally equivalent analog to Midgaard's charter-revocation proceedings.
Charter revocation for institutional oath violations follows a parallel logic: the institution loses its charter, officers lose legal standing, and reinstatement requires demonstrated remediation.
Midgaard's difference from Khardaan's system: Midgaard's revocation proceedings require a formal judicial hearing before designation, while Khardaan's oathbroken classification could be issued by a commanding officer during active crisis.
This difference matters because several Khardaan oathbroken designations were issued by officers who themselves were later found to have violated custody obligations.
Midgaard's registry has flagged these cases: an oathbroken designation issued by an oathbreaker has uncertain legal standing under Midgaard's evidentiary standards.
The Continuity faction considers this a historical technicality: the underlying violations were real regardless of who issued the designation.
The Reckoning faction argues that if Midgaard is going to treat Khardaan precedent as valid, it must apply Midgaard's evidentiary standards consistently, including to disputed designations.
The question is academically unresolved. It has not produced active litigation because there are no surviving parties with standing to contest the designations.

