---
Kowloon's Black Ledger references the Oathbroken Cohorts in its section on crisis-period oath failures and their institutional consequences.
The Neon Covenant's crisis protocol was designed with the cohorts' failure modes explicitly in mind: custody obligations are specified in writing, not assumed from institutional role.
Kowloon's specific response to the cohorts' pattern of record destruction: all Kowloon crisis operations include a standing obligation to preserve administrative records even during evacuation.
Records travel first. Personnel travel second. Equipment travels third. This ordering is counterintuitive but reflects Kowloon's analysis of what failures cost most.
A unit can be reconstituted. Records cannot be reconstructed from memory. The Oathbroken Cohorts who destroyed records created irreversible losses; the cohorts who abandoned civilians created recoverable losses.
Kowloon does not view civilian abandonment as acceptable — it views it as a lesser failure than record destruction in terms of long-term institutional damage.
This prioritization is controversial. Kowloon's internal training materials acknowledge the controversy and explain the reasoning: records are the basis for accountability, and destroying accountability evidence compounds every other failure.
The Black Ledger notes: all but two of the named Oathbroken Cohorts destroyed records. The two that did not are the only ones whose violations could be specifically documented and specifically adjudicated.
The others' violations are known by category but not by detail. Kowloon considers this the strongest argument for record preservation as the primary custody obligation.

