Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine engages with the Oathbroken Cohorts through the question of what information the oath-breaking was designed to suppress.
Several of the cohorts are described in Khardaan memory as having destroyed records that would have documented their commanding officers' orders, not their own violations.
These cases represent a specific failure mode: oath-breaking commanded from above but executed by those below, with record destruction designed to protect the commanders rather than the cohort.
Under Kiess's three-power review requirements, commands to destroy records would require authorization from all three branches and public disclosure of the authorization's purpose.
If even one branch refused, the command could not be executed. Kiess argues this structure would have prevented the record-destruction cases among the Oathbroken Cohorts.
The counter-argument is that crisis conditions make three-power review impractical. Kiess's response: the crisis conditions that make review impractical are exactly the conditions in which review is most necessary.
Kiess's frontier march operations include a standing rule: no record destruction without three-branch authorization. The rule has never been invoked during an active crisis.
Kiess considers this reassuring rather than evidence that the rule is unnecessary. The rule's existence changes the decision calculus before the crisis. You cannot invoke a rule you didn't establish.

