---
Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw treats the Oathbroken Cohorts as the largest-scale historical case of collective oath violation in the corridor's documented record.
The Shrine's interest is analytical: collective oath violation produces different adjudication problems than individual oath violation.
When an individual breaks an oath, the adjudication is straightforward: identify the breach, assess the harm, impose the remedy.
When a unit collectively breaks an oath, the adjudication faces distributed responsibility: each member participated in a collective action for which individual culpability varies.
Khardaan's oathbroken designation addressed this by treating the collective as the responsible party: the unit lost standing, not individual members severally.
The Shrine considers this a reasonable approach but incomplete: collective designation without individual assessment creates incentives for individuals to hide behind collective designation.
Mafdet's Swift Court handles collective oath violations by combining collective designation with individual assessment: the group is formally designated, then each member is individually reviewed for degree of culpability.
This two-stage process was developed partly in response to Shrine analysis of the Oathbroken Cohorts' cases and the inadequacy of collective-only adjudication.
The Claw Mark Registry now includes a collective oath violation sub-category that requires individual review within twelve tides of collective designation.

